{"aid": "40156924", "title": "The Prisoner's Dilemma of Non-Competes", "url": "https://marginalrevolution.com/marginalrevolution/2024/04/the-prisoners-dilemma-of-non-competes.html", "domain": "marginalrevolution.com", "votes": 1, "user": "mhb", "posted_at": "2024-04-25 12:54:29", "comments": 0, "source_title": "The Prisoner\u2019s Dilemma of Non-Competes", "source_text": "The Prisoner's Dilemma of Non-Competes - Marginal REVOLUTION\n\nThank-you! You've been successfully added to the Marginal Revolution email\nsubscription list.\n\n# The Prisoner\u2019s Dilemma of Non-Competes\n\nby Alex Tabarrok April 25, 2024 at 7:11 am in\n\n  * Current Affairs\n  * Economics\n  * Law\n\nI agree with Tyler, that the FTC ban on non-competes is overly broad and not\ntailored to fields where the drawbacks outweigh the benefits. Additionally,\nthe FTC\u2019s authority to enact this rule, rather than Congress, is questionable.\n\nNevertheless, I don\u2019t think banning non-competes is without merit. The reason\nis not the standard Twitter-econ view that non-competes are bad for workers.\nIndeed, some non-competes, so-called \u201cgardening leave\u201d, pay the worker during\nthe non-compete period. Sounds pretty good! More generally, non-competes are\njust one item in the wage bargain like hours, health and pension benefits. As\na result, the FTC is quite wrong to think that banning non-competes will raise\nwages\u2013the most immediate effect will be to reduce wages. Indeed, more workers\nwill be willing to work at lower wages precisely to the extent that non-\ncompetes were a burden. Can\u2019t have it both ways. Instead of being bad for\nworkers, my skepticism about non-competes is that they are bad for industry.\n\nThe problem with non-competes is that every firm wants non-competes on the\nworkers it fires but no firm wants non-competes on the workers it hires.\nHowever, firms only control the terms on which they hire workers so it\u2019s\npossible for each firm acting in its self-interest to create a situation which\nis in the interests of none. Or, to put it differently, firms may approve of\nthe decision to ban non-competes because it\u2019s a package deal, firms can\u2019t\nrestrict their own former employees but they gain the ability to recruit\nfreely from competitors.\n\nMore generally, worker mobility often carries externalities. As I wrote\nearlier, ideas are in heads and if you don\u2019t move the heads, often the ideas\ndon\u2019t move either. The innovation that results from mobility is a public good.\nNon-competes are a type of intellectual property, call it intellect property.\nOnce again, firms want to lock up their intellectual property but they also\nwant to use ideas from other firms. Firms only control the former decision not\nthe latter so IP in general has a prisoner\u2019s dilemma issue which is one reason\nIP in the US is too strong (see the Tabarrok Curve) and non-competes are part\nof that package. Ultimately, if the innovation effects are important, wages\ncould rise but those effects would be for more or less all workers not\nspecifically for those with non-competes.\n\nGovernments aren\u2019t good at the fine details of optimizing IP so perhaps a\nheavy-handed approach is the best we can expect. Non-competes also aren\u2019t a\nhuge issue for most firms, even firms that use them, so given the above I am\nwilling to give the experiment a try.\n\n  * 33 Comments\n\n  * Facebook\n  * Twitter\n  * RSS Feed\n\n  * print\n\n## Comments\n\n### abitoftruth\n\n2024-04-25 07:43:12\n\n35| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nIf the companies were all reasonable (for example always paying for the time\nperiod that was covering the non compete) there would have been no action\ntaken.\n\nI got an internship through my college when I was 20 and had to sign a non-\ncompete with the company. When I graduated there was a recession and the\ncompany had no positions available for me to apply to.\n\nThe next company (same industry, different products) required me to obtain a\nwaiver from the first company. They at first refused to give me one and\nclaimed it was FOREVER (this was before constraints from lawsuits). I went to\nmy college explaining that their partner companies were preventing me from\ngaining employment with the degree they had bestowed in an entire industry my\ninternship was for, FOREVER.\n\nWhile the company did end up writing a release due to the pressure from the\ncollege (except for the type of products I worked on and with a 2 year time\nlimit) it was ridiculous in the first place that my job prospects were\nliterally put at risk, the significant time I had to spend and the stress of\nnot knowing the outcome.\n\nI for one am glad to see it die the death it deserves.\n\nRespond\n\n### asdf\n\n2024-04-25 09:27:41\n\n3| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nMy experience has been that employers try to force a non-compete on you after\nyou've been hired. They will have some stock program that you need to agree to\nthe non-compete to get the stock, but if you refuse the stock you are fired.\nIf they asked for the non-compete as part of your employment you might have\nturned down the job, but once you're working turning it down means immediate\nunemployment. Clearly a screw job tactic.\n\nRespond\n\n### Hmmmm\n\n2024-04-25 09:39:49\n\n1| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nAre you equally glad to picture Tyler holding Ya.na C0wen down on the couch\nand ruthlessly penetrate her teeny-tiny little nubile pussy with his ginormous\nmember? With Alex watching from the side stroking his recessed chin nervously?\n\nRespond\n\n### Publius\n\n2024-04-25 09:37:35\n\n0| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nWell said.\n\nCompanies abused non-compete clauses by applying them in cases where they\nfailed to serve their stated purpose. Now, defenders of those clauses use\nmotte and bailey arguments to point to the uncommon cases where they may\nprovide benefit.\n\nRespond\n\n### Publius\n\n2024-04-25 09:38:08\n\n0| 0  \n---|---