 this isn't an ideal rule, but an ideal rule wasn't plausibly\non the table. It's telling that when we have a choice between non-ideal rules,\nAlex and Tyler are very much on the side of the people with the most power,\neven when it's not clear that this is supported by evidence.\n\nRespond\n\n### OldCurmudgeon\n\n2024-04-25 09:42:45\n\n1| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nThat line struck me as hopelessly naive too.\n\nOK, MAYBE very highly compensated employees can bargain here. But random line\nemployees? They are mostly worried about how they are going to feed their\nfamilies.\n\nRespond\n\n### Prester John\n\n2024-04-25 09:05:59\n\n0| 1  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nIt\u2019s weird to someone so obviously fail a reading comprehension test that\nwasn\u2019t even a test. Alex fairly clearly states that he\u2019s willing to try it\nout; in other words he does not oppose it.\n\nAnd the people in this situation with the most power aren\u2019t the employers but\nthe regulators.\n\nRespond\n\n### Grant Gould\n\n2024-04-25 08:22:38\n\n7| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nFYI, the new rule explicitly allows \"garden leave\" and other arrangements\nwhere the worker is still being paid during the noncompete period.\n\nRespond\n\n### Matt\n\n2024-04-25 08:29:35\n\n8| 1  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nWait, you're saying that Alex is maybe not giving a clear picture, or is, at\nbest, not really informed on something he's expressing a strong opinion on?\nAnd that he's coming down on the side of the powerful? I'm shocked, shocked, I\ntell you!\n\nRespond\n\n### PHinton\n\n2024-04-25 09:13:36\n\n2| 2  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\n> FYI, the new rule explicitly allows \"garden leave\" and other arrangements\n> where the worker is still being paid during the noncompete period.\n\nYes, garden leave is the correct way to handle ALL of this. If the employer is\nso convinced that your residual knowledge must remain on the sidelines, then\nthe former employer pay the employee NOT work for anyone else until they (the\nformer employer) have deemed the former employer's knowledge stale.\n\nRespond\n\n### OldCurmudgeon\n\n2024-04-25 09:40:30\n\n0| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nEven there, it probably should be limited in time. One's existing skills do\ndecline a bit during extended breaks (c.f., mothers returning to the workplace\nwhen their kids go to school)\n\nRespond\n\n### Russell\n\n2024-04-25 07:30:33\n\n6| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nAt least in the UK non competes are only enforceable if they are reasonable.\nSo they won't be enforced if too long or too broad. The trouble is that you\ndon't know in advance if it is reasonable so at least banning them is a bright\nline.\n\nRespond\n\n### dan1111\n\n2024-04-25 07:41:28\n\n6| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nYour point about non-competes being part of worker's wage bargaining makes\nsense, but there are countervailing reasons why banning them could raise\nwages:\n\n1) This ruling frees a large number of workers who are currently locked in\nplace to hit the competitive job market. That seems likely to at least lead to\na short term boost in wages: new opportunities to move to a higher salary,\nplus more incentives to pay top workers to stay where they are.\n\n2) Workers' value doesn't remain static over time. Suppose a company hires 10\nworkers early in their careers. They are all locked in place with non-\ncompetes. One of those workers becomes a rock star, generating millions for\nthe company. The non-compete clause prevents that worker from fully\nrenegotiating their pay to reflect their new value, so eliminating the clauses\ncould raise the pay of these ten workers on average, even if they all started\nat a somewhat lower salary in the absence of the clauses.\n\n3) It's not a zero sum game. If non-competes are a net negative on innovation,\nas argued here, then eliminating them should spur new economic activity, and\nworkers should capture some of the value of that (the FTC--credit where it's\ndue, stopped clocks are occasionally right, etc., etc.,--seems to be making\nthat argument in its announcement).\n\nRespond\n\n### steve\n\n2024-04-25 09:03:27\n\n1| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nAlex and Tyler both seem to be claiming that non-competes increase wages as\ndogma based upon some rigid thinking. In some cases it might be true but there\nare obvious cases where it is not. If in a given area everyone has noncompetes\nif you want/need to work in that area you have to sign a non compete and you\naccept it as cost of working at that place, not that you are being paid extra.\nIt wont increase pay. What it will do is keep you from moving to another job\nin that area where you earn more money. It's also pretty obvious, I know\nseveral examples, where employers were pretty abusive of staff knowing they\ncouldn't leave and get another job without moving and that moving would\ninflict major costs.\n\nI would expect that if eliminated employers would instead sometimes have to\npay people more to keep them from leaving. Your number 2 above is an obvious\nexample but even if you have two competitors in an area and one is performing\nmuch better it wouldn't be unusual to offer more pay as a way to try to lure\npeople away from the less successful competitor. They wont be able to do that\nwith noncompetes.\n\nSo there are probably, surely, some idealized examples where for an individual\ncontract you do have to pay people more in order to get them to sign a\nnoncompete, but as they are commonly used it doesnt increase pay, it only\ndecreases mobility, locking in employees under conditions that may have\nchanged.\n\nSteve\n\nRespond\n\n### Eric chase\n\n2024-04-25 08:31:51\n\n3| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nI work in radio. Every single contract of mine has had a non compete. Which\nwas fine, because I ensure that my severance matched the term of the NC. If\nNCs go away so might severance, and 6 paid months to make important decisions\nis nice.\n\nRespond\n\n### H\n\n2024-04-25 08:05:38\n\n2| 0  \