r not? Basically from recent history it appears that it mostly is not (slight\nexceptions if the president is a Republican apply).\n\nRespond\n\n### HelloHello\n\n2024-04-25 09:35:02\n\n0| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nAlex makes the point that this is FTC overreach in the second sentence of the\npost.\n\nRespond\n\n### Ricardo\n\n2024-04-25 09:24:25\n\n1| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\n\"Indeed, some non-competes, so-called \u201cgardening leave\u201d, pay the worker during\nthe non-compete period. Sounds pretty good!\"\n\nYes, but this is otherwise known as a term-based contract. Nothing wrong with\nthat but it doesn't apply to 99% of workers out there, who are at-will\nemployees.\n\n\"More generally, non-competes are just one item in the wage bargain like\nhours, health and pension benefits.\"\n\nFirst, a sleazy practice that pops up from time to time is that non-compete\nagreements are buried in the onboarding paperwork that someone is asked to\nsign after they already accept the offer and, typically, hand in notice to\ntheir current employer. That is unethical and ought to be illegal. It also\nundermines the premise that we are in a world of nearly perfect competition\nwhere all relevant information is available to both parties. Second, job\nseekers who only have one offer on the table or who are in a difficult\nfinancial situation are unlikely to have the confidence to negotiate on either\ncompensation or the terms of the non-compete.\n\nRespond\n\n### Bruce raben\n\n2024-04-25 07:42:56\n\n1| 1  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nUltimately this is about IP both patents but also trade secrets and know how.\nCompanies want to steal other companies IP through hiring and protect theirs\nthrough non competes.\n\nI think a better but imperfect and in place technique is via Confidentiality\nAgreements. Of course it is hard to literally go inside someone\u2019s brain and\nsee what is in what compartment. The confidentiality compartment and the free\nhuman being compartment.\n\nIn California it is widely acknowledged that non competes are not enforceable\nand eve. Though the state is screwed up in many ways it seem to remain\nintellectually innovative without non competes. However when there is\nsubstantial \u201cconsideration \u201c, like millions of dollars when your company is\npurchased then non-competes are appropriate. The FTC doesn\u2019t really know what\nit is doing\n\nRespond\n\n### Ricardo\n\n2024-04-25 09:37:28\n\n2| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nInformation behind patents is public, though, so that cannot be a\njustification. Access to trade secrets are the only legitimate justification\nbut non-competes are widely abused and applied to people who have little or no\ngenuinely valuable trade secrets. Most notoriously, some fast food restaurants\nmake their employees sign non-competes and Amazon made its warehouse workers\nsign one several years ago.\n\nMost of the time, it is just a naked abuse of workers who need a job more than\nthe employer needs each one of them individually. Other times, it is HR apathy\nand laziness because the new HR manager is using templates downloaded off the\ninternet or stole the templates (ironically) from a previous employer and\nthese templates had non-compete clauses in them.\n\nAs already mentioned here, the FTC rule does indeed allow an exception when\nthere is substantial consideration -- a $151,164 salary is enough -- and when\nthe job is a \"policy-making position\" so I don't know what your beef is.\n\nRespond\n\n### blue jay\n\n2024-04-25 09:14:08\n\n0| 2  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\n\"The FTC doesn\u2019t really know what it is doing\"\n\n+10\n\nIf the net outcome of any given FTC decision under Khan is positive, it's just\ndumb luck. Even a fool makes a \"right\" decision now and again, even if it's\nfor all the wrong reasons.\n\nRespond\n\n### nf\n\n2024-04-25 08:54:12\n\n1| 1  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nLets hoist some non competes on academia and make them compete against Indian\nyoutubers for students.\n\nGuarantee you the economics field would \u201crealize\u201d that free trade isnt good\nand non competes suck.\n\nRespond\n\n### rayward\n\n2024-04-25 09:33:20\n\n0| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nI already provided my real-world comment at Cowen's blog post on the subject.\nI will comment on the exclusion of lawyers from non-competes. The rationale\n(or rationalization) for the ethics rule (prohibiting non-competes) is that\nclients choose lawyers, and it would interfere with the attorney-client\nrelationship to impose non-competes on lawyers. It's ironic that it's an\nethical rule. Why? I have seen very successful law firms implode when the\nlawyers stop billing their clients. Why would they do that? Duh. This has\nimportant implications for any professional practice. Doctors don't have such\na rule, and most employment agreements with doctors have broad non-compete\nprovisions (not in California), including both geographic restrictions and\nnon-solicitation (although as I indicated in my other comment, the trend is\nfor courts not to enforce geographic restrictions). Here's a fun fact: the\nconcentration in the medical industry, with hospitals employing doctors (more\nthan 50% of doctors are employed by hospitals) and the development of large\nsingle and multi-specialty group practices, non-competes have become even\nbroader (the geographic market territory of hospitals and large group\npractices is much larger than the small medical practice) and the bargaining\npower of the individual physician has been greatly reduced. In these parts,\nlarge is beautiful (monopolies sublime). That doesn't seem particularly\nlibertarian to me, but what do I know: I live in the real world.\n\nRespond\n\n### Ricardo\n\n2024-04-25 09:55:31\n\n0| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nThe fact that non-competes apply to doctors but not lawyers is the ultimate\nspecial pleading. Of course people choose their doctors, too. Lawyers get to\nremain a profession while doctors increasingly become working stiff and\nsalary-men and -women subject to KPIs and performance management systems\nrolled out from HQ.\n\nIt is almost as if lawyers get to write the rules. Oh, wait...\n\nRespond\n\nRespond\n\n### Marginal Revolution University\n\nSee Courses\n\n### Learn more about Mercatus Center Fellowships\n\nLearn More\n\n### Subscribe via Email\n\n  * RSS Feed\n\n## Contact Us\n\nAlex Tabarrok Email Alex Follow @atabarrok\n\nTyler Cowen Email Tyler Follow @tylercowen\n\nWebmaster Report an issue\n\n  * Blogs We Like\n  * Interesting People & Sites\n\n## Our Web Pages\n\n  * Alex Tabarrok's Home Page\n  * Alex's TED talk, how ideas trump crises\n  * Conversations with Tyler\n  * FDAReview.org\n  * Tyler Cowen's Personal Web Page\n  * Tyler's ethnic dining guide\n  * Apply to Emergent Ventures\n\n## Books\n\n### Modern Principles of Economics\n\nTyler Cowen & Alexander Tabarrok\n\nMarginal Revolution 2024\n\n  * About Marginal Revolution\n  * Categories\n  * Date Archives\n  * Our Books\n  * Our Textbook: Modern Principles of Economics\n  * Marginal Revolution University\n  *     * Facebook\n    * Twitter\n    * RSS Feed\n  * ### Marginal Revolution University\n\nSee Courses\n\nPrivacy Policy Marginal Revolution 2024\n\n", "frontpage": false}
